{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491584"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"990"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/990"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.4,0.13,0.44,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/990"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"602"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19189"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a three week history of increasing numbness in his right hand and weakness when trying to grip things. The numbness affects his fourth and fifth fingers and is associated with a sudden, sharp pain going from his right shoulder down the inside of his arm to the wrist. The only abnormalities on physical examination are reduced grip strength in the right hand and reduced pinprick sensation in his fifth finger.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carpal tunnel syndrome","Ulnar neuropathy","Brachial plexus neuralgia","Cervical radiculopathy","Lacunar infarction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe distribution of the paraesthesia and the grip weakness indicates a C8 \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical radiculopathy.\u003C/strong\u003E The pain extending from the shoulder to the wrist is also indicative of a proximal nerve root injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E affects the median nerve and the triceps reflex would not be affected by an ulnar nerve lesion. It characteristically affects individuals with risk factors that increase pressure within the carpal tunnel, such as a labourer or women during the latter stages of gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachial plexus problem\u003C/strong\u003E would be most unlikely to be limited to a single nerve root. These lesions characteristically affect numerous nerve distributions and are preceded by an injury, such as birth trauma for erbs (C5-6) and klumpke (C8-T1) palsy. Compressive lesions such as a Pancoast tumour in the apex of the lung may also produce this picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elacunar infarction\u003C/strong\u003E is an infarct affecting the motor fibres of the internal capsule, which would cause pure motor deficits. Other lacunar syndromes can affect the thalamus causing sensory deficits. Lacunar syndromes are characterised by stroke symptoms without cortical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the numbness in the fingers could be consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E, this would not explain pain going down from his shoulders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical radiculopathy affects a single nerve root"],"references":["Carette S and Fehlings MG. Clinical practice. Cervical radiculopathy. N Engl J Med 2005 Jul 29; 353:392.","Stoker GE, Kim HJ, Riew KD. Differentiating c8-t1 radiculopathy from ulnar neuropathy: a survey of 24 spine surgeons. Global Spine J. 2014;4(1):1-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"990"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38816"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-19T20:52:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-19T20:52:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"990"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},